Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/holdingStartOn
Object: Relates a peerage holding to the date on which that peerage holding starts - being the date the peerage is granted to the first holder, the date a hereditary peerage is inherited or the date on which a writ of acceleration is granted.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/degree
Object: Relates a rank to a number representing the degree of that rank in the hierarchy of peerages. The lower the number the higher the degree of the rank, for example: the rank of Barony has a degree of 5, whilst the rank of Dukedom has a degree of 1. Included in the dataset are records for Princes of Wales which are not peerages and given a rank of 0.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasPeerageHolding
Object: Relates a person to a peerage holding. A person may have one or more peerage holdings, or none. A peerage holding is by one person.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/announcedOn
Object: Relates an announcement of a peerage to the date on which that announcement was made.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/RankLabel
Object: The label of a rank, determined by the gender of the person holding a peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasRankLabel
Object: Relates a rank to a rank label. A rank has one of two rank labels in accordance with the gender of a person holding a peerage of that rank, for example: a person holding a peerage with the rank of Earldom has the rank label Earl or Countess. A rank label belongs to one rank.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasGender
Object: Relates a person to their gender.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/previousTitleHasKingdom
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the kingdom of the previous title borne by its recipient, as it appeared on the Letters Patent. Where a Letters Patent has a previous title with a kingdom, it has only one.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Announcement
Object: An announcement of the creation of a peerage - or peerages - for one or more people. An announcement is followed by the issuing of a Letters Patent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/PeerageHolding
Object: The holding of a peerage by a person between two dates. A life peerage will have a single peerage holding. A hereditary peerage may have more than one peerage holding over time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/reignOf
Object: Relates a reign to a monarch during that reign. The reign of William and Mary is considered as a joint reign. A monarch may have more than one reign in more than one kingdom, for example: the reigns of George III in Great Britain, in Ireland and later in the United Kingdom.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/inJurisdiction
Object: Relates a Law Lord incumbency to the jurisdiction in which the appointee held office or practised. A Law Lord incumbency is in one jurisdiction. A jurisdiction may have more than one incumbent Law Lord.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/presentedOn
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the date on which it was presented at a meeting of the Privy Council.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/title
Object: Relates a peerage to the title of the peerage, being the part of the peerage name other than rank, 'of' and territorial designation. For example: 'Plymouth' being the title for 'Earl of Plymouth, in the County of Devon'.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/LawLordIncumbency
Object: An incumbency period for a peerage held by a person appointed to the role of a Law Lord.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasPeerageType
Object: Relates a peerage to its type. A peerage is of one type. A type has more than one peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/AnnouncementType
Object: The type of an announcement, for example: a Dissolution Honours List, initial peerages created under the Life Peerages Act 1958, or a Times report.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Kingdom
Object: The kingdom within which a peerage is created. After 1801, the name of the division within the peerage of the United Kingdom. Kingdom is used in this model to denote what is usually known as the peerage of a kingdom, for example: the Kingdom of Scotland denotes the Peerage of the Kingdom of Scotland. We avoid using the word peerage because this is already used to describe a single title, for example: the peerage of the Earldom of Plymouth.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasLawLordIncumbency
Object: Relates a peerage to an incumbency as a Law Lord. A Law Lord incumbency is for one peerage. A peerage may have one or more Law Lord incumbencies, or none - it being possible for a Law Lord to resign and be reappointed.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/ofTitle
Object: Relates a peerage to a flag indicating if the peerage has an 'of' between the rank and the title. For a peerage such as Earl of Plymouth, this flag is true. For a peerage such as Earl Nelson, this flag is false.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasSpecialRemainder
Object: Relates a peerage to any special remainder applying to that peerage. Where a peerage has a special remainder, it has only one. Types of special remainder may apply to more than one peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/ordinalityOnDate
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to its ordinality on the date of presentation. This is used as a proxy for precedence. A peerage of a higher rank will have a lower ordinality - and greater precedence - than a peerage of a lower rank whose Letters Patent are presented on the same day. For peerages of the same rank presented on the same day, precedence is determined by the time of day at which the Letters Patent was presented. A peerage whose Letters Patent is presented earlier in the day is determined to have a greater precedence - and lower ordinality - than a peerage of the same rank whose Letters Patent is presented later in that day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/holdingEndOn
Object: Relates a peerage holding to the date on which that holding ceases - being the date of death of the holder of the peerage, the date on which the holder is deprived of their title under the Titles Deprivation Act 1917, the date on which the holder is attainted or the date on which the peerage merges into the Crown.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/isOf
Object: Relates a peerage holding to the peerage the holding is of. A peerage holding is of one peerage. A peerage may have one or more peerage holdings.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/previousOfTitle
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to a flag indicating if the title previously borne by the recipient, as it appeared on the Letters Patent, has an 'of' between the rank and the title. For a title such as Earl of Plymouth, this flag is true. For a title such as Earl Nelson, this flag is false.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/ofKingdom
Object: Relates a peerage to the kingdom in which the peerage was created.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Peerage
Object: A specific named title of nobility held within the system of peerages of the United Kingdom and nations.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/
Object: A model describing peerages, the holding of peerage by a person, Letters Patent affirming the creation of a peerage - and kingdoms, monarchs and reigns as they apply to peerages.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/appointedOn
Object: Relates a Law Lord incumbency to the date on which that Law Lord was appointed.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Gender
Object: The gender of a person, for example: male.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/territorialDesignation
Object: Relates a peerage to the territorial designation of that peerage, for example: 'in the County of Devon' being the territorial designation for 'Earl of Plymouth, in the County of Devon'.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/SpecialRemainder
Object: A hereditary peerage is created with rules governing who might inherit, known as a remainder. In the United Kingdom the default remainder allows inheritance by direct male descendants only, whereas in the Kingdom of Scotland both male and female direct descendants may inherit. Peerages are created with special remainders wherever default rules do not apply.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Rank
Object: The rank of a peerage. Ranks vary between kingdoms, for example: in the Kingdom of Scotland the lowest rank is Lordship, whilst in the Kingdoms of England, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, the lowest rank is Barony.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/previousRank
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the rank of the previous title borne by its recipient, as it appeared on the Letters Patent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/ordinality
Object: Relates a peerage holding to the number of the holder in line of succession of that peerage, for example: the '1'st, '2'nd and '3'rd Earls of Onslow.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/LettersPatent
Object: The document affirming that the monarch has created a peerage for a person.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/numberOfLastHolder
Object: Relates a peerage to the ordinality in line of succession of the last holder of that peerage, for example: a peerage becoming extinct with the 11th holder, will have the value 11.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Jurisdiction
Object: The jurisdiction of a Law Lord, being England and Wales, Ireland, Northern Ireland or Scotland.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/announces
Object: Relates an announcement to the Letters Patent - and the peerages whose creation that Letters Patent affirms - being announced. An announcement may announce more than one Letters Patent. A Letters Patent is the subject of one announcement.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/during
Object: Relates an announcement to the government administration period during which that announcement was made.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/appliesTo
Object: Relates a rank label to the gender it applies to. A rank label applies to one gender, for example: a female person holding an Earldom has the rank label Countess. A gender has more than one rank label according to the rank of the peerage, for example: a female person holding a peerage in the Kingdom of Scotland may be a Lady, Viscountess, Countess, Marchioness or Duchess.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/previousTitle
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to that part of the title previously borne by the recipient other than rank, 'of' and any territorial designation, for example: 'Plymouth' being the title for 'Earl of Plymouth, in the County of Devon'.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasRank
Object: Relates a peerage to the rank of that peerage. A peerage has one rank. A rank may apply to more than one peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasAnnouncementType
Object: Relates an announcement to the type of that announcement. An announcement is of one type.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/PeerageType
Object: The type of a peerage, for example: a hereditary peerage, or a life peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/extinctOn
Object: Relates a peerage to the date on which that peerage became extinct, being the date of death of the last holder. For a life peerage, the first holder being the last holder.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/presentedAt
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the recorded time of day at which it was presented at a meeting of the Privy Council. A Letters Patent may only have one recorded time in a day. A recorded time in a day may refer to more than one Letters Patent, issued across different days, for example: '10 am', referring to any number of Letters Patent issued at that time on different days. A recorded time may only have one Letters Patent on one day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/LettersPatentTime
Object: The time of day of a meeting of the Privy Council at which the Letters Patent was presented, as recorded in the Gazette. This may be morning or afternoon or a given hour.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/inKingdom
Object: Relates a rank to a kingdom in which a peerage of that rank may be created. A kingdom has peerages of more than one rank. A rank may be found in one or more kingdoms.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/hasKingdom
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the kingdom in which that Letters Patent was issued. A Letters Patent belongs to one kingdom. A kingdom may have more than one Letters Patent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Reign
Object: A period of time during which a monarch has a reign in a kingdom.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/affirmsCreationOf
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to a peerage it affirms the creation of. A Letters Patent may affirm the creation of one or more peerages, always for the same person. The creation of a peerage is affirmed by one Letters Patent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/issuedIn
Object: Relates a Letters Patent to the reign in which that Letters Patent was issued. A Letters Patent is issued in one reign. One or more Letters Patent may be issued in a reign.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/mergedIntoTheCrownOn
Object: Relates a peerage to the date on which that peerage merged into the Crown. Any peerages held by an heir to the throne will be merged into the Crown when that heir succeeds.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/GovernmentAdministrationPeriod
Object: A period of a single government, under a single Prime Minister, bounded by general elections, for example: Thatcher administration 1979-1983, Thatcher administration 1983-1987, Thatcher administration 1987-1990.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/receives
Object: Relates a person to a Letters Patent that person is in receipt of, affirming the creation of a peerage for that person. A person may receive one or more Letters Patent, or none. A Letters Patent is received by one person.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/Monarch
Object: A person reigning within a kingdom.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/reignIn
Object: Relates a reign to a kingdom the reign is in. A reign has one kingdom. A kingdom may have more than one reign over time, but only one reign at one time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/gazetteUrl
Object: Relates an announcement to the URL of the record of that announcement in the edition of the Gazette in which that announcement appears.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/peerage/description
Object: Relates a special remainder to a textual description of that special remainder.
